      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. the problem is we're in a constrained environment so we can't really run Valgrind or heavy static analysis tools right on the hardware. we basically only have access to some basic logging and a debugger. \n\nif i can't use those heavy tools, how can i more effectively narrow down which specific modules or objects are 'eating' the memory over time? is there a way to track it without completely tanking the real-time performance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right; running heavy tools like Valgrind on a constrained automotive MCU is a recipe for a system crash, and that's the last thing you want after a 4-6 hour leak. Since you're limited to basic logging and a debugger, you need a \"lightweight\" strategy that doesn't slow down the main control loop.\n\nThe best approach here is to implement a **custom, lightweight heap monitor** that runs in a separate, low-priority task or a dedicated interrupt handler, rather than instrumenting every single line of your main loop. Think of it like a tiny, invisible \"goblin\" that watches the memory heap in the background, recording every time a new block is allocated or freed, without actually touching the blocks themselves.\n\nHere is a systematic way to do this without tanking performance:\n\n1.  **Implement a \"Goblin-Style\" Heap Logger**:\n    Instead of using standard `new`/`delete`, create wrapper functions that log the allocation size and location to a circular buffer. Since you can't afford to log to the UART every millisecond, use a **circular buffer** that only writes to a file or a specific memory region when the buffer is full or",
      "source": "target",
